<kml>

<concept name=Damage><system-documentation name=Damage>
<superconcept name=Impair>

<definition>
  Damage an object (which does not have to be a living thing) so it becomes worse or less 
  effective. The object can still perform its function, but at a diminished capacity.
</definition>

<requiredslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=object>
     The object that's damaged. The object does not have to be a living thing.
  </slotdescription>

</requiredslotlist>

<primaryslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=agent>
    the entity that caused the damage to occur.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=instrument>
    the thing that was used to damage the object.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=by-means-of>
    the event that caused the damage to occur.
  </slotdescription>

</primaryslotlist>

<examplesentencelist>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>John damaged the TV with a bat.</text>
    <slotdescription name=agent>John</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=object>the TV</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=instrument>a bat</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>
     The TV becomes worse and less effective, but it is not broken. If the
     TV becomes broken, then use <conceptref name=Break> to describe the 
     action.
  </comment>

</examplesentencelist>

<neighborlist>

  <neighbor name=Impair>
     An impair is a general kind of damage where there is no restriction on the object.
  </neighbor>

  <neighbor name=Break>
     A break is a special kind of damage where the object is broken and
     can no longer perform its function.
  </neighbor>

  <neighbor name=Harm>
     A harm is similar to a damage, but the object being harmed is a living thing. 
  </neighbor>

</neighborlist>

</kml>


